{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2016}}
The [[2018 Under-19 Cricket World Cup]] in New Zealand will be contested by sixteen teams, eleven of which qualified automatically. The other five places in the tournament will be determined by a series of regional qualifiers, with one place being granted to each [[International Cricket Council]] (ICC) development region ([[ICC Africa|Africa]], the [[ICC Americas|Americas]], [[Asian Cricket Council|Asia]], [[ICC East Asia-Pacific|East Asia-Pacific]], and [[ICC Europe|Europe]]). 

==Automatic qualification==
The ten full members of the ICC as at 2016 qualified automatically for the [[Under-19 Cricket World Cup|Under-19 World Cup]]. In early 2016, it was determined that the top-placed ICC [[Associate membership of the ICC|associate member]] at the [[2016 Under-19 Cricket World Cup|2016 Under-19 World Cup]] in Bangladesh would also qualify automatically for the 2018 event. That team was [[Namibia national under-19 cricket team|Namibia]], which defeated another associate member, [[Nepal national under-19 cricket team|Nepal]], in the seventh-place play-off.<ref>[http://www.espncricinfo.com/icc-under-19-world-cup-2016/content/story/971401.html "Namibia Under-19s qualify for 2018 World Cup"], ESPNcricinfo, 11 February 2016. Retrieved 29 July 2016.</ref>

==Regional qualification==

===Africa===
====Division Two====
The Africa Division Two tournament was played in [[Benoni, Gauteng]], South Africa, from 10–18 September 2016. [[Ghana national under-19 cricket team|Ghana]] (the winner) and [[Botswana national under-19 cricket team|Botswana]] (the runner-up) both qualified for Division One.<ref>[http://www.icc-cricket.com/news/2016/media-releases/96158/ghana-wins-icc-u19-cwc-qualifiers-africa-division-2 "Ghana wins ICC U19 CWC Qualifiers – Africa Division 2"], ICC, 19 September 2016. Retrieved 24 September 2016.</ref>
