{{Infobox recurring event | name = Washington State Apple Blossom Festival | native_name = | logo = | logo_caption = | image = Apple blossoms.jpg | imagesize = 250px | caption = Apple blossoms in early spring | date = | begins = late April | ends = early May | frequency = annual | location = [[Wenatchee, Washington]] | years_active = | first = 1920 | last = | participants = | attendance = 100,000 (2011) | genre = | budget = | patron = | website = [http://www.appleblossom.org/ appleblossoms.org] | footnotes = }} The '''Washington State Apple Blossom Festival''' is a [[festival]] held annually in [[Wenatchee, Washington|Wenatchee]], [[Washington (state)|Washington]] from the last weekend in April to the first weekend in May. The festival, first held in 1920,<ref>{{cite web| publisher=National Phenology Network| title=Washington State Apple Blossom Festival| accessdate=2012-03-22| url=http://www.usanpn.org/node/3971}}</ref> has grown from a one-day event to an eleven-day affair including a [[carnival]], golf tournament, food fair, multiple parades, an arts and crafts fair, entertainment on a stage in Memorial Park, and other amusements.<ref>{{cite web| publisher=The Seattle Traveler| title=Washington State Apple Blossom Festival in Wenatchee| accessdate=2012-03-22| url=http://www.theseattletraveler.com/2007/04/washington-state-apple-blossom-festival-in-wenatchee/}}</ref>
==History== The Washington State Apple Blossom Festival, originally called "Blossom Days", was founded in 1919 to celebrate the importance of the [[apple]] industry to the region. The Ladies Musical Club produced the first festival in 1920, a one-day event in Memorial Park involving songs, speeches, [[Maypole|maypoles]], and baseball. The festival's relative success in drawing in large crowds from the area assured the continuation of the festival in subsequent years. In 1921, the Commercial Club, forerunner of the Wenatchee Valley Chamber of Commerce, took over sponsorship of the celebration.<ref name=homepage>{{cite web| title=Our History| publisher=Washington State Apple Blossom Festival| accessdate=2012-03-22| url=http://www.appleblossom.org/about/history/apple-blossom-history.html}}</ref>
When the festival began again after [[World War II]], the festival was renamed the Washington State Apple Blossom Festival to more accurately reflect the importance of the [[Horticulture industry|apple industry]] in North [[Central Washington]].<ref name=homepage/>
In 1967, Wenatchee established a [[sister city]] relationship with the Aomori Apple Blossom Festival in [[Japan]].<ref name=homepage/>
